description: Morphologically vein +‎ -ous, which is a borrowing from Latin vēnōsus (“full of veins, veiny”), from vēna (“a blood vessel, vein”) +‎ -ōsus (“-ous, -ose”, adjectival suffix). Doublet of venose.

adjectives.description: venous (comparative more venous, superlative most venous)

examples: Her venous circulation was poor, leading to varicose veins.

entries.meaning: (relational, of blood) Having passed through the capillaries and given up oxygen for the tissues and become charged with carbon dioxide.

examples: It was a sample of venous tissue.
The tree has highly serrated and venous leaves.
